# CLAUDE.md, <Project>

<!--
  CLAUDE.md is the per-project instructions file that Claude Code reads at the
  start of every session in this repository. Put standing context here: things
  that are true across many sessions, not notes about today's task.

  Keep it under about 200 lines. When a section wants to grow past a short
  paragraph, move the depth into a document and leave a pointer. A long file
  costs attention on every single session, including the ones where that
  section is irrelevant.

  Delete any heading you do not need. An empty section is worse than a missing
  one, because it reads as an answer.
-->

## Project Overview

One paragraph. What this is and who it is for.

## Tech Stack

The frameworks and services actually in use. Name the ones a newcomer would not guess.

## Project Structure

A short folder map. Only the directories someone needs to find their way.

## Key Concepts

Domain vocabulary. Any word this codebase uses in a specific way, defined in one line each. This section prevents more confusion than any other.

## Data Schema

Either the model itself if it is small, or a pointer to where it lives.

## Environment Variables

Which variables exist and what each is for. Never the values. Point at `.env.example`.

## Authentication

How a request proves who it is, and where that is enforced.

## Testing

The commands to run, and what level of coverage is expected before something counts as done.

## MANDATORY: QA Before Claiming Done

The hard gate. Spell out what has to be true before any work is reported as finished, in checkable terms.

Passing unit tests is usually not sufficient on its own. If this project has a user interface, say that the actual journey has to be walked in a browser or on a device, because tests that pass while the real flow is broken is the most common way work gets reported as done when it is not.

## Coding Conventions

Only the ones that are not obvious from reading the code.

## Document Ownership

Name exactly one authoritative source per kind of fact, and have everything else cross-reference it.

| Fact | Owned by |
|---|---|
| Architecture decisions | `DECISIONS.md` |
| Test counts and history | `docs/testing.md` |
| Roadmap | `ROADMAP.md` |

Without this, the same number drifts across four files and nobody can tell which one is right.

## Key Reference Documents

A pointer list. What to read, and when it is worth reading.

## What to Consult Before Making Changes

The preflight. Which files to open before touching which areas.

## Known Technical Debt

The shortcuts currently in place, and the condition under which each stops being acceptable. A shortcut with a named trigger is a decision. Without one it is a landmine.

## Context Budget

Any guidance about what not to load. Useful in a large repository where the obvious approach reads far too much.

## Self-Review Before Declaring Done

Keep this last, deliberately. It is the final thing in context before the assistant reports back, which is exactly when it needs to be remembered.

- [ ] Does this do what was actually asked, rather than what was convenient?
- [ ] Has it been run, not just written?
- [ ] Would the QA gate above pass right now?
- [ ] Is anything claimed here unverified? Say so explicitly rather than implying it was checked.
